<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:18.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>6. Architecture principles prioritized in this c=
ase</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>1) Least privilege</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Support use=
rs,
internal operations, fraud staff, and vendors must not have broad access to
customer data or card-related records without approved, role-based, and
preferably time-bound access. This aligns with both general best practice a=
nd
the stronger governance posture expected in MAS TRM. <a
href=3D"https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/server/api/core/bitstrea=
ms/fa20beb3-d2df-4d2b-bc12-dab3462dfacd/content">[openresear...anu.edu.au]<=
/a>,
<a href=3D"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/53/r5/upd1/final">[csrc.nist.g=
ov]</a></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>2) Defense in depth</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Do not rely=
 only
on login security. Combine MFA / strong auth patterns, session controls,
authorization checks, API protection, secure coding, detective controls, and
fraud monitoring. ASVS and the AWS Security Pillar both support layered
controls and defense-in-depth. <a
href=3D"https://owasp.org/www-project-application-security-verification-sta=
ndard/">[owasp.org]</a>,
<a
href=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/wellarchitected/latest/security-pillar/=
welcome.html">[docs.aws.amazon.com]</a></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>3) Secure by design</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Security
requirements must be established during design, not added after UAT. MAS TRM
explicitly emphasizes security-by-design and SDLC controls. <a
href=3D"https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/server/api/core/bitstrea=
ms/fa20beb3-d2df-4d2b-bc12-dab3462dfacd/content">[openresear...anu.edu.au]<=
/a>,
<a
href=3D"https://www.pwc.com/sg/en/risk-assurance/assets/revisions-to-guidel=
ines-on-technology-risk-management.pdf">[pwc.com]</a></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>4) Strong identity and authorization</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>This case is
heavily authorization-sensitive: customer-to-object ownership, role separat=
ion,
support access, privileged access. ASVS gives strong requirement-level cove=
rage
for authentication, session, authorization, tokens, and data protection. <a
href=3D"https://owasp.org/www-project-application-security-verification-sta=
ndard/">[owasp.org]</a>,
<a href=3D"https://asvs.dev/">[asvs.dev]</a></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>5) Auditability and accountability</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Every
customer-sensitive or privileged action must be attributable and reviewable.
MAS TRM, NIST 800-53, and AWS Security Pillar all reinforce logging,
governance, and traceability. <a
href=3D"https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/server/api/core/bitstrea=
ms/fa20beb3-d2df-4d2b-bc12-dab3462dfacd/content">[openresear...anu.edu.au]<=
/a>,
<a href=3D"https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/53/r5/upd1/final">[csrc.nist.g=
ov]</a>,
<a
href=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/wellarchitected/latest/framework/securi=
ty.html">[docs.aws.amazon.com]</a></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;line-height:15pt;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0p=
t'>&nbsp;</p>

