<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:18.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>7. Architecture principles prioritized in this c=
ase</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>1) Data protection through lifecycle</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>This case is
document-heavy. The primary risk is often not the database itself, but stor=
age
links, downloads, exports, support paths, and internal overexposure.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>2) Least privilege</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Internal ro=
les
should only see cases/documents required for their function.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>3) Segmentation and role separation</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Customer,
reviewer, finance/compliance, and admin roles must be separated.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:16.0pt'><span
style=3D'font-weight:bold'>4) Secure file handling</span></p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:"Segoe UI";font-size:10.5pt'>Uploads,
scanning, storage, retrieval, access links, retention, and deletion must al=
